# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: timescaledb
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:timescaledb/about-compression] This page gives an in-depth explanation of the compression methods used in hypercore.
[src:timescaledb/about-compression] For integers, timestamps, and other integer-like types TimescaleDB uses a combination of delta encoding, delta-of-delta, simple 8-b, and run-length encoding.
[src:timescaledb/about-compression] The simple-8b compression method has been extended so that data can be decompressed in reverse order.
[src:timescaledb/about-compression] Backward scanning queries are common in time-series workloads.
[src:timescaledb/about-compression] This means that these types of queries run much faster.
[src:timescaledb/about-compression] Delta encoding reduces the amount of information required to represent a data object by only storing the difference, sometimes referred to as the delta, between that object and one or more reference objects.
[src:timescaledb/about-compression] These algorithms work best where there is a lot of redundant information, and it is often used in workloads like versioned file systems.
[src:timescaledb/about-compression] For example, this is how Dropbox keeps your files synchronized.
[src:timescaledb/about-compression] Applying delta-encoding to time-series data means that you can use fewer bytes to represent a data point, because you only need to store the delta from the previous data point.
[src:timescaledb/about-compression] For example, imagine you had a dataset that collected CPU, free memory, temperature, and humidity over time.
[src:timescaledb/about-compression] With delta encoding, you only need to store how much each value changed from the previous data point, resulting in smaller values to store.
[src:timescaledb/about-compression] Applying delta encoding to time-series data takes advantage of the fact that most time-series datasets are not random, but instead represent something that is slowly changing over time.
[src:timescaledb/about-compression] The storage savings over millions of rows can be substantial, especially if the value changes very little, or doesn't change at all.
[src:timescaledb/about-compression] Delta-of-delta encoding takes delta encoding one step further and applies delta-encoding over data that has previously been delta-encoded.
[src:timescaledb/about-compression] With time-series datasets where data collection happens at regular intervals, you can apply delta-of-delta encoding to the time column, which results in only needing to store a series of zeroes.
[src:timescaledb/about-compression] In other words, delta encoding stores the first derivative of the dataset, while delta-of-delta encoding stores the second derivative of the dataset.
[src:timescaledb/about-compression] In this example, delta-of-delta further compresses 5 seconds in the time column down to 0 for every entry in the time column after the second row, because the five second gap remains constant for each entry.
[src:timescaledb/about-compression] Note that you see two entries in the table before the delta-delta 0 values, because you need two deltas to compare.
[src:timescaledb/about-compression] This compresses a full timestamp of 8 bytes, or 64 bits, down to just a single bit, resulting in 64x compression.
[src:timescaledb/about-compression] With delta and delta-of-delta encoding, you can significantly reduce the number of digits you need to store.
[src:timescaledb/about-compression] But you still need an efficient way to store the smaller integers.
[src:timescaledb/about-compression] The previous examples used a standard integer datatype for the time column, which needs 64 bits to represent the value of 0 when delta-delta encoded.
[src:timescaledb/about-compression] This means that even though you are only storing the integer 0, you are still consuming 64 bits to store it, so you haven't actually saved anything.
[src:timescaledb/about-compression] Simple-8b is one of the simplest and smallest methods of storing variable-length integers.
[src:timescaledb/about-compression] In this method, integers are stored as a series of fixed-size blocks.
[src:timescaledb/about-compression] For each block, every integer within the block is represented by the minimal bit-length needed to represent the largest integer in that block.
[src:timescaledb/about-compression] The first bits of each block denotes the minimum bit-length for the block.
[src:timescaledb/about-compression] This technique has the advantage of only needing to store the length once for a given block, instead of once for each integer.
[src:timescaledb/about-compression] Because the blocks are of a fixed size, you can infer the number of integers in each block from the size of the integers being stored.
[src:timescaledb/about-compression] In this example, both blocks store about 10 digits worth of data, even though some of the numbers have to be padded with a leading 0.
[src:timescaledb/about-compression] You might also notice that the second block only stores 9 digits, because 10 is not evenly divisible by 3.
[src:timescaledb/about-compression] Simple-8b works in this way, except it uses binary numbers instead of decimal, and it usually uses 64-bit blocks.
[src:timescaledb/about-compression] In general, the longer the integer, the fewer number of integers that can be stored in each block.
[src:timescaledb/about-compression] Simple-8b compresses integers very well, however, if you have a large number of repeats of the same value, you can get even better compression with run-length encoding.
[src:timescaledb/about-compression] This method works well for values that don't change very often, or if an earlier transformation removes the changes.
[src:timescaledb/about-compression] Run-length encoding is one of the classic compression algorithms.
[src:timescaledb/about-compression] For time-series data with billions of contiguous zeroes, or even a document with a million identically repeated strings, run-length encoding works incredibly well.
[src:timescaledb/about-compression] For values like these, you do not need to store each instance of the value, but rather how long the run, or number of repeats, is.
[src:timescaledb/about-compression] Run-length encoding is also used as a building block for many more advanced algorithms, such as Simple-8b RLE, which is an algorithm that combines run-length and Simple-8b techniques.
[src:timescaledb/about-compression] TimescaleDB implements a variant of Simple-8b RLE.
[src:timescaledb/about-compression] This variant uses different sizes to standard Simple-8b, in order to handle 64-bit values, and RLE.
[src:timescaledb/about-compression] For columns that do not have a high amount of repeated values, TimescaleDB uses XOR-based compression.
[src:timescaledb/about-compression] The standard XOR-based compression method has been extended so that data can be decompressed in reverse order.
[src:timescaledb/about-compression] This means that queries that use backwards scans run much faster.
[src:timescaledb/about-compression] Floating point numbers are usually more difficult to compress than integers.
[src:timescaledb/about-compression] Fixed-length integers often have leading zeroes, but floating point numbers usually use all of their available bits, especially if they are converted from decimal numbers, which can't be represented precisely in binary.
[src:timescaledb/about-compression] Techniques like delta-encoding don't work well for floats, because they do not reduce the number of bits sufficiently.
[src:timescaledb/about-compression] This means that most floating-point compression algorithms tend to be either complex and slow, or truncate significant digits.
[src:timescaledb/about-compression] One of the few simple and fast lossless floating-point compression algorithms is XOR-based compression, built on top of Facebook's Gorilla compression.
[src:timescaledb/about-compression] XOR is the binary function `exclusive or`.
[src:timescaledb/about-compression] In this algorithm, successive floating point numbers are compared with XOR, and a difference results in a bit being stored.
[src:timescaledb/about-compression] The first data point is stored without compression, and subsequent data points are represented using their XOR'd values.
[src:timescaledb/about-compression] For values that are not integers or floating point, TimescaleDB uses dictionary compression.
[src:timescaledb/about-compression] One of the earliest lossless compression algorithms, dictionary compression is the basis of many popular compression methods.
[src:timescaledb/about-compression] Dictionary compression can also be found in areas outside of computer science, such as medical coding.
[src:timescaledb/about-compression] Instead of storing values directly, dictionary compression works by making a list of the possible values that can appear, and then storing an index into a dictionary containing the unique values.
[src:timescaledb/about-compression] This technique is quite versatile, can be used regardless of data type, and works especially well when you have a limited set of values that repeat frequently.
[src:timescaledb/about-compression] For a dataset with a lot of repetition, this can offer significant compression.
[src:timescaledb/about-compression] In the example, each city name is on average 11 bytes in length, while the indices are never going to be more than 4 bytes long, reducing space usage nearly 3 times.
[src:timescaledb/about-compression] In TimescaleDB, the list of indices is compressed even further with the Simple-8b+RLE method, making the storage cost even smaller.
[src:timescaledb/about-compression] Dictionary compression doesn't always result in savings.
[src:timescaledb/about-compression] If your dataset doesn't have a lot of repeated values, then the dictionary is the same size as the original data.
[src:timescaledb/about-compression] TimescaleDB automatically detects this case, and falls back to not using a dictionary in that scenario.
[src:timescaledb/about-compression] **PostgreSQL TOAST compression**: if dictionary compression does not perform, TimescaleDB skips compression and allows PostgreSQL to handle the data using Oversized-Attribute Storage Technique (TOAST) compression.
[src:timescaledb/about-compression] By default, PostgreSQL uses `pglz` compression.
[src:timescaledb/about-compression] To configure PostgreSQL to use more modern compression algorithms like `lz4`, set the `default_toast_compression` configuration parameter.
[src:timescaledb/about-continuous-aggregates] In modern applications, data usually grows very quickly.
[src:timescaledb/about-continuous-aggregates] This means that aggregating it into useful summaries can become very slow.
[src:timescaledb/about-continuous-aggregates] If you are collecting data very frequently, you might want to aggregate your data into minutes or hours instead.
[src:timescaledb/about-continuous-aggregates] For example, if an IoT device takes temperature readings every second, you might want to find the average temperature for each hour.
[src:timescaledb/about-continuous-aggregates] Every time you run this query, the database needs to scan the entire table and recalculate the average.
[src:timescaledb/about-continuous-aggregates] TimescaleDB makes aggregating data lightning fast, accurate, and easy with continuous aggregates.
[src:timescaledb/about-continuous-aggregates] Continuous aggregates in TimescaleDB are a kind of hypertable that is refreshed automatically in the background as new data is added, or old data is modified.
[src:timescaledb/about-continuous-aggregates] Changes to your dataset are tracked, and the hypertable behind the continuous aggregate is automatically updated in the background.
[src:timescaledb/about-continuous-aggregates] Continuous aggregates have a much lower maintenance burden than regular PostgreSQL materialized views, because the whole view is not created from scratch on each refresh.
[src:timescaledb/about-continuous-aggregates] This means that you can get on with working your data instead of maintaining your database.
[src:timescaledb/about-continuous-aggregates] Because continuous aggregates are based on hypertables, you can query them in exactly the same way as your other tables.
[src:timescaledb/about-continuous-aggregates] This includes continuous aggregates in the rowstore, compressed into the columnstore, or tiered to object storage.
[src:timescaledb/about-continuous-aggregates] You can even create continuous aggregates on top of your continuous aggregates, for an even more fine-tuned aggregation.
[src:timescaledb/about-continuous-aggregates] Real-time aggregation enables you to combine pre-aggregated data from the materialized view with the most recent raw data.
[src:timescaledb/about-continuous-aggregates] This gives you up-to-date results on every query.
[src:timescaledb/about-continuous-aggregates] In TimescaleDB v2.13 and later, real-time aggregates are **DISABLED** by default.
[src:timescaledb/about-continuous-aggregates] In earlier versions, real-time aggregates are **ENABLED** by default; when you create a continuous aggregate, queries to that view include the results from the most recent raw data.
[src:timescaledb/about-continuous-aggregates] There are three main ways to make aggregation easier: materialized views, continuous aggregates, and real-time aggregates.
[src:timescaledb/about-continuous-aggregates] Materialized views are a standard PostgreSQL function.
[src:timescaledb/about-continuous-aggregates] They are used to cache the result of a complex query so that you can reuse it later on.
[src:timescaledb/about-continuous-aggregates] Materialized views do not update regularly, although you can manually refresh them as required.
[src:timescaledb/about-continuous-aggregates] Continuous aggregates are a TimescaleDB-only feature.
[src:timescaledb/about-continuous-aggregates] They work in a similar way to a materialized view, but they are updated automatically in the background, as new data is added to your database.
[src:timescaledb/about-continuous-aggregates] Continuous aggregates are updated continuously and incrementally, which means they are less resource intensive to maintain than materialized views.
[src:timescaledb/about-continuous-aggregates] Continuous aggregates are based on hypertables, and you can query them in the same way as you do your other tables.
[src:timescaledb/about-continuous-aggregates] Real-time aggregates are a TimescaleDB-only feature.
[src:timescaledb/about-continuous-aggregates] They are the same as continuous aggregates, but they add the most recent raw data to the previously aggregated data to provide accurate and up-to-date results, without needing to aggregate data as it is being written.
[src:timescaledb/about-continuous-aggregates] You can create a continuous aggregate on top of another continuous aggregate.
[src:timescaledb/about-continuous-aggregates] This allows you to summarize data at different granularity.
[src:timescaledb/about-continuous-aggregates] For example, you might have a raw hypertable that contains second-by-second data.
[src:timescaledb/about-continuous-aggregates] Create a continuous aggregate on the hypertable to calculate hourly data.
[src:timescaledb/about-continuous-aggregates] To calculate daily data, create a continuous aggregate on top of your hourly continuous aggregate.
[src:timescaledb/about-continuous-aggregates] For more information, see the documentation about continuous aggregates on continuous aggregates.
[src:timescaledb/about-continuous-aggregates] When you create a hypertable using CREATE TABLE ...
[src:timescaledb/about-continuous-aggregates] WITH ..., the default partitioning column is automatically the first column with a timestamp data type.
[src:timescaledb/about-continuous-aggregates] Also, TimescaleDB creates a columnstore policy that automatically converts your data to the columnstore, after an interval equal to the value of the chunk_interval, defined through `after` in the policy.
[src:timescaledb/about-continuous-aggregates] This columnar format enables fast scanning and aggregation, optimizing performance for analytical workloads while also saving significant storage space.
[src:timescaledb/about-continuous-aggregates] In the columnstore conversion, hypertable chunks are compressed by up to 98%, and organized for efficient, large-scale queries.
[src:timescaledb/about-continuous-aggregates] You can customize this policy later using alter_job.
[src:timescaledb/about-continuous-aggregates] However, to change `after` or `created_before`, the compression settings, or the hypertable the policy is acting on, you must remove the columnstore policy and add a new one.
[src:timescaledb/about-continuous-aggregates] You can also manually convert chunks in a hypertable to the columnstore.
[src:timescaledb/about-continuous-aggregates] In TimescaleDB v2.7 and later, continuous aggregates support all PostgreSQL aggregate functions.
[src:timescaledb/about-continuous-aggregates] This includes both parallelizable aggregates, such as `SUM` and `AVG`, and non-parallelizable aggregates, such as `RANK`.
[src:timescaledb/about-continuous-aggregates] In TimescaleDB v2.10.0 and later, the `FROM` clause supports `JOINS`, with some restrictions.
[src:timescaledb/about-continuous-aggregates] For more information, see the `JOIN` support section.
[src:timescaledb/about-continuous-aggregates] In older versions of TimescaleDB, continuous aggregates only support aggregate functions that can be parallelized by PostgreSQL.
[src:timescaledb/about-continuous-aggregates] You can work around this by aggregating the other parts of your query in the continuous aggregate, then using the window function to query the aggregate.
[src:timescaledb/about-continuous-aggregates] DISTINCT works in aggregate functions, not in the query definition.
[src:timescaledb/about-continuous-aggregates] If you want the old behavior in later versions of TimescaleDB, set the `timescaledb.finalized` parameter to `false` when you create your continuous aggregate.
[src:timescaledb/about-continuous-aggregates] Continuous aggregates take raw data from the original hypertable, aggregate it, and store the aggregated data in a materialization hypertable.
[src:timescaledb/about-continuous-aggregates] When you query the continuous aggregate view, the aggregated data is returned to you as needed.
[src:timescaledb/about-continuous-aggregates] The materialization table is stored as a TimescaleDB hypertable, to take advantage of the scaling and query optimizations that hypertables offer.
[src:timescaledb/about-continuous-aggregates] Materialization tables contain a column for each group-by clause in the query, and an `aggregate` column for each aggregate in the query.
[src:timescaledb/about-continuous-aggregates] For more information, see materialized hypertables.
[src:timescaledb/about-continuous-aggregates] The materialization engine performs two transactions.
[src:timescaledb/about-continuous-aggregates] The first transaction blocks all INSERTs, UPDATEs, and DELETEs, determines the time range to materialize, and updates the invalidation threshold.
[src:timescaledb/about-continuous-aggregates] The second transaction unblocks other transactions, and materializes the aggregates.
[src:timescaledb/about-continuous-aggregates] The first transaction is very quick, and most of the work happens during the second transaction, to ensure that the work does not interfere with other operations.
[src:timescaledb/about-continuous-aggregates] Any change to the data in a hypertable could potentially invalidate some materialized rows.
[src:timescaledb/about-continuous-aggregates] The invalidation engine checks to ensure that the system does not become swamped with invalidations.
[src:timescaledb/about-continuous-aggregates] Fortunately, time-series data means that nearly all INSERTs and UPDATEs have a recent timestamp, so the invalidation engine does not materialize all the data, but to a set point in time called the materialization threshold.
[src:timescaledb/about-continuous-aggregates] This threshold is set so that the vast majority of INSERTs contain more recent timestamps.
[src:timescaledb/about-continuous-aggregates] These data points have never been materialized by the continuous aggregate, so there is no additional work needed to notify the continuous aggregate that they have been added.
[src:timescaledb/about-continuous-aggregates] When the materializer next runs, it is responsible for determining how much new data can be materialized without invalidating the continuous aggregate.
[src:timescaledb/about-continuous-aggregates] It then materializes the more recent data and moves the materialization threshold forward in time.
[src:timescaledb/about-continuous-aggregates] This ensures that the threshold lags behind the point-in-time where data changes are common, and that most INSERTs do not require any extra writes.
[src:timescaledb/about-continuous-aggregates] When data older than the invalidation threshold is changed, each transaction logs the minimum and maximum timestamps of the rows it modified.
[src:timescaledb/about-continuous-aggregates] The continuous aggregate then identifies which complete time buckets are affected based on this per-transaction tracking.
[src:timescaledb/about-continuous-aggregates] This logging does cause some write load.
[src:timescaledb/about-continuous-aggregates] However, the threshold lags behind the area of data that is currently changing, so the writes are small and rare.
[src:timescaledb/latest-hypertables] Tiger Cloud supercharges your real-time analytics by letting you run complex queries continuously, with near-zero latency.
[src:timescaledb/latest-hypertables] Under the hood, this is achieved by using hypertables, PostgreSQL tables that automatically partition your time-series data by time and optionally by other dimensions.
[src:timescaledb/latest-hypertables] When you run a query, Tiger Cloud identifies the correct partition, called chunk, and runs the query on it, instead of going through the entire table.
[src:timescaledb/latest-hypertables] To top it all, there is no added complexity, you interact with hypertables in the same way as you would with regular PostgreSQL tables.
[src:timescaledb/latest-hypertables] All the optimization magic happens behind the scenes.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] The PostgreSQL Global Development Group focuses only on developing a database engine and closely related components.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] This core is, technically, what comprises PostgreSQL itself, but there is an extensive developer community and ecosystem that provides other important feature sets that might, traditionally, be provided by a proprietary software vendor.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] These include special-purpose database engine features, like those needed to support a geospatial or temporal database or features which emulate other database products.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] Also available from third parties are a wide variety of user and machine interface features, such as graphical user interfaces or load balancing and high availability toolsets.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] The large third-party PostgreSQL support network of people, companies, products, and projects, even though not part of The PostgreSQL Development Group, are essential to the PostgreSQL database engine's adoption and use and make up the PostgreSQL ecosystem writ large.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] PostgreSQL was originally named POSTGRES, referring to its origins as a successor to the Ingres database developed at the University of California, Berkeley.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] In 1996, the project was renamed PostgreSQL to reflect its support for SQL.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] After a review in 2007, the development team decided to keep the name PostgreSQL and the alias Postgres.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] PostgreSQL evolved from the Ingres project at the University of California, Berkeley.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] In 1982, the leader of the Ingres team, Michael Stonebraker, left Berkeley to make a proprietary version of Ingres.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] He returned to Berkeley in 1985, and began a post-Ingres project to address the problems with contemporary database systems that had become increasingly clear during the early 1980s.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] He won the Turing Award in 2014 for these and other projects, and techniques pioneered in them.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] The new project, POSTGRES, aimed to add the fewest features needed to completely support data types.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] These features included the ability to define types and to fully describe relationships – something used widely, but maintained entirely by the user.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] In POSTGRES, the database understood relationships, and could retrieve information in related tables in a natural way using *rules*.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] POSTGRES used many of the ideas of Ingres, but not its code.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] Starting in 1986, published papers described the basis of the system, and a prototype version was shown at the 1988 ACM SIGMOD Conference.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] The team released version 1 to a small number of users in June 1989, followed by version 2 with a re-written rules system in June 1990.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] Version 3, released in 1991, again re-wrote the rules system, and added support for multiple storage managers and an improved query engine.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] By 1993, the number of users began to overwhelm the project with requests for support and features.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] After releasing version 4.2 on June 30, 1994 – primarily a cleanup – the project ended.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] Berkeley released POSTGRES under an MIT License variant, which enabled other developers to use the code for any use.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] At the time, POSTGRES used an Ingres-influenced POSTQUEL query language interpreter, which could be interactively used with a console application named monitor.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] In 1994, Berkeley graduate students Andrew Yu and Jolly Chen replaced the POSTQUEL query language interpreter with one for the SQL query language, creating Postgres95.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] The monitor console was also replaced by psql.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] Yu and Chen announced the first version (0.01) to beta testers on May 5, 1995.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] Version 1.0 of Postgres95 was announced on September 5, 1995, with a more liberal license that enabled the software to be freely modifiable.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] On July 8, 1996, Marc Fournier at Hub.org Networking Services provided the first non-university development server for the open-source development effort.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] With the participation of Bruce Momjian and Vadim B.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] Mikheev, work began to stabilize the code inherited from Berkeley.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] In 1996, the project was renamed to PostgreSQL to reflect its support for SQL.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] The online presence at the website PostgreSQL.org began on October 22, 1996.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] The first PostgreSQL release formed version 6.0 on January 29, 1997.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] Since then developers and volunteers around the world have maintained the software as The PostgreSQL Global Development Group.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] The project continues to make releases available under its free and open-source software PostgreSQL License.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] Code comes from contributions from proprietary vendors, support companies, and open-source programmers.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] As of 2025, PostgreSQL is on major release version 18 which is notable in implementing asynchronous I/O (AIO), enabling database users to perform concurrent I/O tasks like readahead and sequential scan.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] PostgreSQL manages concurrency through multiversion concurrency control (MVCC), which gives each transaction a "snapshot" of the database, allowing changes to be made without affecting other transactions.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] This largely eliminates the need for read locks, and ensures the database maintains ACID principles.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] PostgreSQL offers four levels of transaction isolation: Read Uncommitted, Read Committed, Repeatable Read and Serializable.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] Because PostgreSQL is immune to dirty reads, requesting a Read Uncommitted transaction isolation level provides read committed instead.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] PostgreSQL supports full serializability via the serializable snapshot isolation (SSI) method.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] The PostgreSQL MVCC implementation is prone to performance issues that require tuning when under a heavy write load which updates existing rows.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] PostgreSQL includes built-in binary replication based on shipping the changes (write-ahead logs (WAL)) to replica nodes asynchronously, with the ability to run read-only queries against these replicated nodes.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] This allows splitting read traffic among multiple nodes efficiently.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] Earlier replication software that allowed similar read scaling normally relied on adding replication triggers to the master, increasing load.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] PostgreSQL includes built-in synchronous replication that ensures that, for each write transaction, the master waits until at least one replica node has written the data to its transaction log.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] Unlike other database systems, the durability of a transaction (whether it is asynchronous or synchronous) can be specified per-database, per-user, per-session or even per-transaction.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] This can be useful for workloads that do not require such guarantees, and may not be wanted for all data as it slows down performance due to the requirement of the confirmation of the transaction reaching the synchronous standby.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] Standby servers can be synchronous or asynchronous.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] Synchronous standby servers can be specified in the configuration which determines which servers are candidates for synchronous replication.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] The first in the list that is actively streaming will be used as the current synchronous server.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] When this fails, the system fails over to the next in line.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] PostgreSQL's replication can trigger conflicts between the primary and standby servers, particularly whenever tuples are prematurely deleted from the standby server despite ongoing queries accessing them.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] To address this, PostgreSQL includes a feedback flag where the standby server proactively informs the primary server of any ongoing queries to mitigate this type of conflict.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] Synchronous multi-master replication is not included in the PostgreSQL core.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] Postgres-XC which is based on PostgreSQL provides scalable synchronous multi-master replication.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] It is licensed under the same license as PostgreSQL.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] A related project is called Postgres-XL.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] Bidirectional replication (BDR) is an asynchronous multi-master replication system for PostgreSQL.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] Tools such as repmgr make managing replication clusters easier.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] Several asynchronous trigger-based replication packages are available.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] PostgreSQL includes built-in support for regular B-tree and hash table indexes, and four index access methods: generalized search trees (GiST), generalized inverted indexes (GIN), Space-Partitioned GiST (SP-GiST) and Block Range Indexes (BRIN).
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] In addition, user-defined index methods can be created, although this is quite an involved process.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] PostgreSQL schemas are namespaces, allowing objects of the same kind and name to co-exist in a single database.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] They are not to be confused with a database schema—the abstract, structural, organizational specification which defines how every table's data relates to data within other tables.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] All PostgreSQL database objects, except for a few global objects such as roles and tablespaces, exist within a schema.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] They cannot be nested, schemas cannot contain schemas.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] The permission system controls access to schemas and their content.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] By default, newly created databases have only a single schema called *public* but other schemas can be added and the public schema isn't mandatory.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] A `search_path` setting determines the order in which PostgreSQL checks schemas for unqualified objects (those without a prefixed schema).
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] By default, it is set to `$user, public` (`$user` refers to the currently connected database user).
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] This default can be set on a database or role level, but as it is a session parameter, it can be freely changed (even multiple times) during a client session, affecting that session only.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] Non-existent schemas, or other schemas not accessible to the logged-in user, that are listed in search_path are silently skipped during object lookup.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] New objects are created in whichever valid schema (one that can be accessed) appears first in the search_path.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] In addition, users can create their own data types which can usually be made fully indexable via PostgreSQL's indexing infrastructures – GiST, GIN, SP-GiST.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] Examples of these include the geographic information system (GIS) data types from the PostGIS project for PostgreSQL.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] There is also a data type called a *domain*, which is the same as any other data type but with optional constraints defined by the creator of that domain.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] This means any data entered into a column using the domain will have to conform to whichever constraints were defined as part of the domain.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] A data type that represents a range of data can be used which are called range types.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] These can be discrete ranges (e.g. all integer values 1 to 10) or continuous ranges (e.g., any time between 10:00 am and 11:00 am).
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] The built-in range types available include ranges of integers, big integers, decimal numbers, time stamps (with and without time zone) and dates.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] Custom range types can be created to make new types of ranges available, such as IP address ranges using the inet type as a base, or float ranges using the float data type as a base.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] Range types support inclusive and exclusive range boundaries using the [] and () characters respectively.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] (e.g., `[4,9)` represents all integers starting from and including 4 up to but not including 9.) Range types are also compatible with existing operators used to check for overlap, containment, right of etc.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] Tables can be set to inherit their characteristics from a *parent* table.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] Data in child tables will appear to exist in the parent tables, unless data is selected from the parent table using the ONLY keyword, i.e.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] Adding a column in the parent table will cause that column to appear in the child table.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] Inheritance can be used to implement table partitioning, using either triggers or rules to direct inserts to the parent table into the proper child tables.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] In particular, table constraints are not currently inheritable.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] All check constraints and not-null constraints on a parent table are automatically inherited by its children.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] Other types of constraints (unique, primary key, and foreign key constraints) are not inherited.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] Inheritance provides a way to map the features of generalization hierarchies depicted in entity–relationship diagrams (ERDs) directly into the PostgreSQL database.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] PostgreSQL can link to other systems to retrieve data via foreign data wrappers (FDWs).
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] These can take the form of any data source, such as a file system, another relational database management system (RDBMS), or a web service.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] This means that regular database queries can use these data sources like regular tables, and even join multiple data-sources together.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] PostgreSQL supports a binary communication protocol that allows applications to connect to the database server.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] The protocol is versioned (currently 3.0, as of PostgreSQL 7.4) and has a detailed specification.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] The official client implementation of this communication protocol is a C API, libpq.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] In addition, the officially supported ECPG tool allows SQL commands to be embedded in C code.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] Both are part of the standard PostgreSQL distribution.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] Third-party libraries for connecting to PostgreSQL are available for many programming languages, including C++, Java, Julia, Python, Node.js, Go, and Rust.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] Procedural languages allow developers to extend the database with custom subroutines (functions), often called *stored procedures*.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] These functions can be used to build database triggers (functions invoked on modification of certain data) and custom data types and aggregate functions.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] Procedural languages can also be invoked without defining a function, using a DO command at SQL level.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] Languages are divided into two groups: Procedures written in *safe* languages are sandboxed and can be safely created and used by any user.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] Procedures written in *unsafe* languages can only be created by superusers, because they allow bypassing a database's security restrictions, but can also access sources external to the database.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] Some languages like Perl provide both safe and unsafe versions.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] In addition, PostgreSQL allows procedural languages to be loaded into the database through extensions.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] Three language extensions are included with PostgreSQL to support Perl, Tcl, and Python.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] For Python, the current Python 3 is used, and the discontinued Python 2 is no longer supported as of PostgreSQL 15.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] Both were supported previously, defaulting to Python 2, while old and new versions couldn't be used in the same session.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] External projects provide support for many other languages, including PL/Java, JavaScript (PL/V8), PL/Julia, PL/R, PL/Ruby, and others.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] Triggers are events triggered by the action of SQL data manipulation language (DML) statements.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] For example, an INSERT statement might activate a trigger that checks if the values of the statement are valid.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] Most triggers are only activated by either INSERT or UPDATE statements.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] Triggers are fully supported and can be attached to tables.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] Triggers can be per-column and conditional, in that UPDATE triggers can target specific columns of a table, and triggers can be told to execute under a set of conditions as specified in the trigger's WHERE clause.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] Triggers can be attached to views by using the INSTEAD OF condition.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] Multiple triggers are fired in alphabetical order.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] In addition to calling functions written in the native PL/pgSQL, triggers can also invoke functions written in other languages like PL/Python or PL/Perl.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] PostgreSQL provides an asynchronous messaging system that is accessed through the NOTIFY, LISTEN and UNLISTEN commands.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] A session can issue a NOTIFY command, along with the user-specified channel and an optional payload, to mark a particular event occurring.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] Other sessions are able to detect these events by issuing a LISTEN command, which can listen to a particular channel.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] This functionality can be used for a wide variety of purposes, such as letting other sessions know when a table has updated or for separate applications to detect when a particular action has been performed.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] Such a system prevents the need for continuous polling by applications to see if anything has yet changed, and reducing unnecessary overhead.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] Notifications are fully transactional, in that messages are not sent until the transaction they were sent from is committed.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] This eliminates the problem of messages being sent for an action being performed which is then rolled back.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] Many connectors for PostgreSQL provide support for this notification system (including libpq, JDBC, Npgsql, psycopg and node.js) so it can be used by external applications.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] PostgreSQL can act as an effective, persistent "pub/sub" server or job server by combining LISTEN with FOR UPDATE SKIP LOCKED.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] Rules allow the "query tree" of an incoming query to be rewritten; they are an, automatically invoked, macro language for SQL.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] "Query Re-Write Rules" are attached to a table/class and "Re-Write" the incoming DML (select, insert, update, and/or delete) into one or more queries that either replace the original DML statement or execute in addition to it.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] Query Re-Write occurs after DML statement parsing and before query planning.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] The functionality rules provide was, in almost every way, later duplicated with the introduction of newer types of triggers.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] The use of triggers is usually preferred over rules as it is easier to reason about trigger behavior and interactions than when equivalent rules are used.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] PostgreSQL server is process-based (not threaded), and uses one operating system process per database session.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] Multiple sessions are automatically spread across all available CPUs by the operating system.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] Many types of queries can also be parallelized across multiple background worker processes, taking advantage of multiple CPUs or cores.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] Client applications can use threads and create multiple database connections from each thread.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] PostgreSQL manages its internal security on a per-role basis.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] A role is generally regarded to be a user (a role that can log in), or a group (a role of which other roles are members).
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] Permissions can be granted or revoked on any object down to the column level, and can allow or prevent the visibility/creation/alteration/deletion of objects at the database, schema, table, and row levels.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] PostgreSQL's SECURITY LABEL feature (extension to SQL standards), allows for additional security; with a bundled loadable module that supports label-based mandatory access control (MAC) based on Security-Enhanced Linux (SELinux) security policy.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] The GSSAPI, SSPI, Kerberos, peer, ident and certificate methods can also use a specified "map" file that lists which users matched by that authentication system are allowed to connect as a specific database user.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] These methods are specified in the cluster's host-based authentication configuration file (pg_hba.conf), which determines what connections are allowed.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] This allows control over which user can connect to which database, where they can connect from (IP address, IP address range, domain socket), which authentication system will be enforced, and whether the connection must use Transport Layer Security (TLS).
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] PostgreSQL claims high, but not complete, conformance with the latest SQL standard ("as of the version 17 release in September 2024, PostgreSQL conforms to at least 170 of the 177 mandatory features for SQL:2023 Core conformance", and no other databases fully conformed to it).
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] One exception is the handling of unquoted identifiers like table or column names.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] In PostgreSQL they are folded, internally, to lower case characters whereas the standard says that unquoted identifiers should be folded to upper case.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] Thus, `Foo` should be equivalent to `FOO` not `foo` according to the standard.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] Other shortcomings concern the absence of temporal tables allowing automatic logging of row versions during transactions with the possibility of browsing in time (FOR SYSTEM TIME predicate), although relatively SQL compliant third-party extensions are available.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] Many informal performance studies of PostgreSQL have been done.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] Performance improvements aimed at improving scalability began heavily with version 8.1.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] Simple benchmarks between version 8.0 and version 8.4 showed that the latter was more than ten times faster on read-only workloads and at least 7.5 times faster on both read and write workloads.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] The first industry-standard and peer-validated benchmark was completed in June 2007, using the Sun Java System Application Server (proprietary version of GlassFish) 9.0 Platform Edition, UltraSPARC T1-based Sun Fire server and PostgreSQL 8.2.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] This result of 778.14 SPECjAppServer2004 JOPS@Standard compares favourably with the 874 JOPS@Standard with Oracle 10 on an Itanium-based HP-UX system.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] In August 2007, Sun submitted an improved benchmark score of 813.73 SPECjAppServer2004 JOPS@Standard.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] With the system under test at a reduced price, the price/performance improved from $84.98/JOPS to $70.57/JOPS.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] The default configuration of PostgreSQL uses only a small amount of dedicated memory for performance-critical purposes such as caching database blocks and sorting.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] This limitation is primarily because older operating systems required kernel changes to allow allocating large blocks of shared memory.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] PostgreSQL.org provides advice on basic recommended performance practice in a wiki.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] In April 2012, Robert Haas of EnterpriseDB demonstrated PostgreSQL 9.2's linear CPU scalability using a server with 64 cores.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] Matloob Khushi performed benchmarking between PostgreSQL 9.0 and MySQL 5.6.15 for their ability to process genomic data.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] In his performance analysis he found that PostgreSQL extracts overlapping genomic regions eight times faster than MySQL using two datasets of 80,000 each forming random human DNA regions.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] Insertion and data uploads in PostgreSQL were also better, although general searching ability of both databases was almost equivalent.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] 64-bit Power ISA), SPARC (also 64-bit), MIPS and PA-RISC.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] It was also known to work on some other platforms (while not been tested on for years, i.e. for latest versions).
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] , which can be used to enter SQL queries directly, or execute them from a file.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] In addition, psql provides a number of meta-commands and various shell-like features to facilitate writing scripts and automating a wide variety of tasks; for example tab completion of object names and SQL syntax.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] (GUI) administration tool for PostgreSQL, which is supported on many computer platforms.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] The program is available in more than a dozen languages.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] The second incarnation (named pgAdmin II) was a complete rewrite, first released on January 16, 2002.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] and then released under the same license as PostgreSQL.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] framework allowing it to run on most common operating systems.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] The query tool includes a scripting language called pgScript for supporting admin and development tasks.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] announced that with the shift towards web-based models, work has begun on pgAdmin 4 with the aim to facilitate cloud deployments.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] PostgreSQL Studio allows users to perform essential PostgreSQL database development tasks from a web-based console.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] PostgreSQL Studio allows users to work with cloud databases without the need to open firewalls.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] AJAX/JavaScript-driven web interface for PostgreSQL.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] Allows browsing, maintaining and creating data and database objects via a web browser.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] management for commonly used scripts, among other features.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] Installers are available for Windows, Macintosh, and Linux, and a simple cross-platform archive that runs from a script.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] Base can be used as a front-end for PostgreSQL.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] The pgBadger PostgreSQL log analyzer generates detailed reports from a PostgreSQL log file.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] pgDevOps is a suite of web tools to install & manage multiple PostgreSQL versions, extensions, and community components, develop SQL queries, monitor running databases and find performance problems.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] is a simple web-based administration tool for PostgreSQL and others, written in PHP.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] pgBackRest is a backup and restore tool for PostgreSQL that provides support for full, differential, and incremental backups.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] pgaudit is a PostgreSQL extension that provides detailed session and/or object audit logging via the standard logging facility provided by PostgreSQL.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] Postgresus is an open source backup tool with GUI for scheduled backups with support of external sources (S3, NAS, FTP, Google Drive, Google Cloud, etc.) and notifications to external services (Slack, Discord, Telegram, SMTP, etc.).
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] A number of companies offer proprietary tools for PostgreSQL.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] They often consist of a universal core that is adapted for various specific database products.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] These tools mostly share the administration features with the open source tools but offer improvements in data modeling, importing, exporting or reporting.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] Due to its permissive open-source license and extensible architecture, a broad ecosystem has developed around PostgreSQL.
[src:timescaledb/postgresql] This includes numerous companies offering dedicated support and hosting, as well as several forks and derivative databases that adapt PostgreSQL for specific workloads.
[src:timescaledb/time-series-database] A **time series database** is a software system that is optimized for storing and serving time series through associated pairs of time(s) and value(s).
[src:timescaledb/time-series-database] In some fields, *time series* may be called profiles, curves, traces or trends.
[src:timescaledb/time-series-database] Several early time series databases are associated with industrial applications which could efficiently store measured values from sensory equipment (also referred to as data historians), but now are used in support of a much wider range of applications.
[src:timescaledb/time-series-database] In many cases, the repositories of time-series data will utilize compression algorithms to manage the data efficiently.
[src:timescaledb/time-series-database] Although it is possible to store time-series data in many different database types, the design of these systems with time as a key index is distinctly different from relational databases which reduce discrete relationships through referential models.
[src:timescaledb/time-series-database] Time series datasets are relatively large and uniform compared to other datasets―usually being composed of a timestamp and associated data.
[src:timescaledb/time-series-database] Time series datasets can also have fewer relationships between data entries in different tables and don't require indefinite storage of entries.
[src:timescaledb/time-series-database] The unique properties of time series datasets mean that time series databases can provide significant improvements in storage space and performance over general purpose databases.
[src:timescaledb/time-series-database] For instance, due to the uniformity of time series data, specialized compression algorithms can provide improvements over regular compression algorithms designed to work on less uniform data.
[src:timescaledb/time-series-database] Time series databases can also be configured to regularly delete (or downsample) old data, unlike regular databases which are designed to store data indefinitely.
[src:timescaledb/time-series-database] Special database indices can also provide boosts in query performance.
[src:timescaledb/time-series-database] Time series databases are commonly designed for append-heavy workloads, where large numbers of measurements or events are continuously written together with timestamps.
[src:timescaledb/time-series-database] Specialized time series management systems have been developed for data from monitoring, automation, the Internet of Things, and cyber-physical systems, where data may be produced at high velocity and in large volumes.
[src:timescaledb/time-series-database] Common design goals include high-throughput data ingestion, low-latency queries over time ranges, efficient compression, and support for aggregation or downsampling over time windows.
[src:timescaledb/time-series-database] Many systems also organize data by tags, devices, sensors, or other metadata, so that users can retrieve measurements by both time range and source.
[src:timescaledb/time-series-database] Time series databases are used in application areas where data is collected continuously over time.
[src:timescaledb/time-series-database] Examples include industrial monitoring, operational historians, infrastructure and application monitoring, Internet of Things sensor data, energy systems, financial market data, and scientific measurements.
[src:timescaledb/time-series-database] In monitoring applications, time series database systems may need to process large amounts of sensor or metric data in real time, execute continuous queries, and support analytical tasks such as data exploration, anomaly detection, predictive modeling, trend analysis, and missing-value recovery.
[src:timescaledb/time-series-database] Time series databases are often used as storage and query systems for downstream analytical tasks, including forecasting, anomaly detection, imputation, and pattern matching.
[src:timescaledb/time-series-database] Some systems also integrate analytical or machine-learning functions closer to the database layer, allowing users to invoke forecasting or anomaly detection through database query interfaces such as SQL.
[src:timescaledb/time-series-database] Recent research in time series analysis has also explored large pre-trained models for tasks such as forecasting, imputation, and anomaly detection.
[src:timescaledb/time-series-database] These models are usually discussed as analytical methods for time series data rather than as defining features of time series databases.
[src:timescaledb/time-series-database] The following database systems have functionality optimized for handling time series data.
[src:timescaledb/timescaledb] One of the key features of TimescaleDB is its performance, which has been compared to InfluxDB.
[src:timescaledb/timescaledb] Time-based data partitioning via hypertables provides for improved query execution and performance when used for time oriented applications.
[src:timescaledb/timescaledb] More granular partition definition is achieved through the use of user defined attributes.
[src:timescaledb/timescaledb] TimescaleDB is offered as open source software under the Apache 2.0 license.
[src:timescaledb/timescaledb] Additional features are offered in a community edition as source available software under the Timescale License Agreement (TLS).
[src:timescaledb/timescaledb] Timescale was founded by Ajay Kulkarni (CEO) and Michael J.
[src:timescaledb/timescaledb] Freedman (CTO) in response to their need for a database solution to support internet of things workloads.
